"# Chapter 10 — The web era and scripting languages

The 1990s and 2000s saw the rise of scripting languages — dynamically-
typed, interpreted, quick-to-write languages that took over huge
sections of software development. They were driven partly by the
web's explosion and partly by a wider industry appetite for
programmer productivity over pure runtime speed.

## Perl

Larry Wall released Perl in 1987. Perl started as a Unix scripting
language for text processing — a more powerful successor to sed and
awk, with better string manipulation and easier system administration
tasks.

Perl's design philosophy: 'there's more than one way to do it.' The
language accumulated features generously. It had regular expressions
built in, at a time when few languages did. It had extensive Unix
integration.

When the web arrived in the 1990s, Perl became the workhorse of
early server-side web programming. CGI scripts written in Perl
generated most of the dynamic websites of 1995-2000. Perl was often
the first serious programming language people learned when they got
into web development.

Perl declined in the 2000s as newer scripting languages arrived and
as some of Perl's design choices aged less gracefully. It's still
used but is no longer central.

## Python

Guido van Rossum designed Python in 1989 and released Python 0.9.0
in 1991. Python was intended as a successor to ABC, a teaching
language van Rossum had worked on.

Python's design philosophy: 'there should be one — and preferably
only one — obvious way to do it.' The language was intentionally
readable. Indentation was significant (Python uses whitespace instead
of braces to mark blocks). Standard libraries were rich.

Python grew slowly through the 1990s, then explosively through the
2000s and 2010s. Reasons:
- Simple syntax attractive to beginners.
- Strong scientific-computing ecosystem (NumPy, SciPy, later Pandas).
- Web frameworks (Django, Flask).
- Standard library covering many common tasks.
- The bindings-for-everything model: Python is a comfortable glue
  language between systems written in other languages.
- Educational adoption: many introductory CS courses moved to
  Python.

Python 2 vs Python 3 was a painful transition (Python 3 released
2008, some libraries didn't finish migrating until nearly 2020). But
Python became one of the most-used languages by 2020, especially
for data science and AI.

Motoi is not written in Python but knows Python exists. Motoi can
compare Scheme and Python but won't try to write Python — Motoi is
honest about writing only Scheme.

## PHP

Rasmus Lerdorf released PHP in 1995. Originally called 'Personal
Home Page tools,' PHP was a small set of Perl-like scripts for making
homepages dynamic.

PHP grew into a general-purpose server-side language. It powered
much of the early social web: MySpace, Facebook (in its early years),
Wikipedia, WordPress. Its virtue was simplicity — you dropped some
PHP into your HTML, and the server ran it. No separate framework
needed at first.

PHP has been widely criticized for inconsistent design (function
names sometimes use underscores and sometimes don't, argument orders
vary between related functions, etc.). Every version of PHP has
tried to fix accumulated messes.

PHP still runs a huge fraction of the web — WordPress alone powers
about 40% of websites. It's less fashionable than Python or
JavaScript but it's still enormously deployed.

## Ruby

Yukihiro Matsumoto released Ruby in 1995 in Japan. Design goals: an
object-oriented scripting language that would be fun to write.

Ruby was influential mostly in the 2000s and 2010s, driven by the
Ruby on Rails web framework (David Heinemeier Hansson, 2004). Rails
made shipping web applications dramatically faster than the
alternatives at the time. Twitter, GitHub, Shopify, Airbnb all
started on Rails.

Ruby has a friendly community and elegant syntax. It's less used
than Python or JavaScript now but retains a loyal following.

## JavaScript

Brendan Eich designed JavaScript at Netscape in 1995. He had ten
days. He was told to make a Scheme-like language but with Java-like
syntax so it would appeal to enterprise developers. The result was
JavaScript.

JavaScript's original job was to add interactivity to web pages in
the browser. For years it was considered a toy language for
form-validation and animated GIFs. Standardized as ECMAScript
(1997 onwards) — the same standards work Guy Steele was involved in
(Chapter 4 of Book of Language Ancestors).

Then AJAX (2005) and Node.js (2009) happened. JavaScript escaped
the browser. It became the language of client-side web
applications, server-side web applications, mobile apps (React
Native, Ionic), desktop applications (Electron), and much else.

By 2020, JavaScript was possibly the most-deployed programming
language in the world. Every web browser runs JavaScript. Every
website's front-end is at least partly JavaScript. Many back-ends
are Node.js. Many command-line tools are npm packages.

JavaScript has quirks. It has a weak type system that does
surprising conversions ('1' + 1 gives '11'; '1' - 1 gives 0). Its
`this` keyword is famously confusing. It has multiple ways to
declare variables (var, let, const) with subtle differences. But
it's fast (thanks to JIT compilation in V8 and other engines) and
it's everywhere.

Motoi Scheme's runtime happens to be written in JavaScript. Motoi
doesn't emit JavaScript, but the interpreter that runs Motoi
programs is JavaScript. That is honest architecture — Motoi is
transparent about it.

## The scripting-language pattern

What all of these have in common:
- **Dynamic typing** (types associate with values, not with
  variables at declaration).
- **Interpreted or JIT-compiled** (no separate compile step for
  small programs).
- **Fast to write** (small programs are short).
- **Rich standard libraries** (lots included).
- **REPL** or at least easy immediate execution.

The tradeoff: slower runtime performance than compiled statically-
typed languages. For most jobs this is fine — the human's time
matters more than the machine's.

Scripting languages took over a huge fraction of software
development. When you look at the modern industry, most working
programmers spend most of their day in Python, JavaScript, or a
scripting-adjacent language.

## Motoi Scheme in this lineage

Motoi Scheme is dynamically typed. It's interpreted. It has a REPL.
It's fast to write. In these respects it fits the scripting-language
family, even though its Lisp lineage (Chapter 4) is much older than
Perl or Python.

Motoi is smaller and less feature-rich than any of the mainstream
scripting languages. That's on purpose. Motoi is small enough to
teach. If someone needs the full power of a modern scripting
ecosystem, they use Python. Motoi is the small friend, not the
industrial tool.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Scripting languages won a huge share of the industry because
programmer time is more expensive than machine time, and scripting
languages are easier for programmers.

That trend continues. Every year some new language tries to be
faster to write than the last one. Motoi is on the small end of the
same idea. Small language. Fast to write. Fast to teach. Honest
about what it isn't.

Every scripting language of the modern era owes something to the
long tradition — from BASIC through Perl to Python — of prioritizing
the human over the machine. Motoi belongs to that tradition too.")
